{"author":{"id":"837b2176f32c8aa0e6451c57f356a863ffced5924eb6264b6c4a7bb61a9eccd0"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1532956417,"nonce":"ViWLth1ltRpbu5hGWtjvFNgdUcM=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUzNDU3NTIyMjE=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/2010","origin":"github"},"title":"New data manager to select indexes that are already on the filesystem.","message":"Hi all,\n\nI am working on a data manager that is very simple. You just specify a table of one of the supported indexes, put in the path on the filesystem, and how you want the entry to be called. It then adds the index to a galaxy data table. Major indexes like `bwa_mem` `bowtie` `star` etc. are supported.\n\nIt's not really a dumb path inputer. It also checks whether the indexes are really there on the filesystem to prevent typing mistakes. It does not check the integrity of the indexes.\n\nAll the functionality is unit tested with pytest and coverage is \u003e 95%.\n\nMy question: would this be a worthy tool to add to tools-iuc or be given the iuc's blessing?\n\nThe data manager can be found here:\nhttps://github.com/LUMC/lumc-galaxy-tools/tree/master/data_manager_select_index_by_path","files":null}]}